1.0.0 ¬∑ [source](about:blank/src/std/f32.rs.html#443-445)

Returns the square root of a number.

Returns NaN if `self` is a negative number other than `-0.0`.

##### [¬ß](#precision-3)Precision

The result of this operation is guaranteed to be the rounded infinite-precision result. It is specified by IEEE 754 as `squareRoot` and guaranteed not to change.

##### [¬ß](#examples-14)Examples

```
let positive = 4.0_f32;
let negative = -4.0_f32;
let negative_zero = -0.0_f32;

assert_eq!(positive.sqrt(), 2.0);
assert!(negative.sqrt().is_nan());
assert!(negative_zero.sqrt() == negative_zero);
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+positive+=+4.0_f32;%0A++++let+negative+=+-4.0_f32;%0A++++let+negative_zero+=+-0.0_f32;%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(positive.sqrt(),+2.0);%0A++++assert!(negative.sqrt().is_nan());%0A++++assert!(negative_zero.sqrt()+==+negative_zero);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.0.0 ¬∑ [source](about:blank/src/std/f32.rs.html#470-472)

Returns `e^(self)`, (the exponential function).

##### [¬ß](#unspecified-precision-2)Unspecified precision

The precision of this function is non-deterministic. This means it varies by platform, Rust version, and can even differ within the same execution from one invocation to the next.

##### [¬ß](#examples-15)Examples

```
let one = 1.0f32;
// e^1
let e = one.exp();

// ln(e) - 1 == 0
let abs_difference = (e.ln() - 1.0).abs();

assert!(abs_difference <= f32::EPSILON);
```

