[source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/num/dec2flt/mod.rs.html#163)[¬ß](#method.from_str)

Converts a string in base 10 to a float. Accepts an optional decimal exponent.

This function accepts strings such as

-   ‚Äò3.14‚Äô
-   ‚Äò-3.14‚Äô
-   ‚Äò2.5E10‚Äô, or equivalently, ‚Äò2.5e10‚Äô
-   ‚Äò2.5E-10‚Äô
-   ‚Äò5.‚Äô
-   ‚Äò.5‚Äô, or, equivalently, ‚Äò0.5‚Äô
-   ‚Äòinf‚Äô, ‚Äò-inf‚Äô, ‚Äò+infinity‚Äô, ‚ÄòNaN‚Äô

Note that alphabetical characters are not case-sensitive.

Leading and trailing whitespace represent an error.

##### [¬ß](#grammar)Grammar

All strings that adhere to the following [EBNF](https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-xml/#sec-notation) grammar when lowercased will result in an [`Ok`](about:blank/result/enum.Result.html#variant.Ok "variant std::result::Result::Ok") being returned:

```txt
Float  ::= Sign? ( 'inf' | 'infinity' | 'nan' | Number )
Number ::= ( Digit+ |
             Digit+ '.' Digit* |
             Digit* '.' Digit+ ) Exp?
Exp    ::= 'e' Sign? Digit+
Sign   ::= [+-]
Digit  ::= [0-9]

```

##### [¬ß](#arguments)Arguments

-   src - A string

##### [¬ß](#return-value)Return value

`Err(ParseFloatError)` if the string did not represent a valid number. Otherwise, `Ok(n)` where `n` is the closest representable floating-point number to the number represented by `src` (following the same rules for rounding as for the results of primitive operations).

[¬ß](#associatedtype.Err)

The associated error which can be returned from parsing.

